.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School" "C Library Functions"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
string and a variable number of arguments.

The
.I format
string is composed of zero or more ordinary characters and
conversion specifications. Ordinary characters are printed as-is.
Conversion specifications start with the character '%'
and are followed by a conversion specifier character.

This implementation handles the following conversion specifiers:

.TP
.B %c
Print a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Print a string of characters. If the corresponding argument is
a null pointer, the string "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Print a literal '%' character. No argument is consumed.

.TP
.B %d, %i
Print a signed decimal integer.

All output is written to the standard output stream (file descriptor 1).

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful return, the
.B _printf()
function returns the number of characters printed (excluding the
terminating null byte used to end strings in C).

If an error occurs, or if
.I format
is NULL, the function returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello, %s\\n", "world");
_printf("Number: %d\\n", 42);
_printf("Percent: %%\\n");
.fi

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3)

.SH AUTHORS
Tom Marchal, David Roset
